                                                                                                                                    IIMC ready for fun fest

     A STAFF REPORTER
               
	Dance, music, theatre, fashion, gaming and lot more will spice up the weekend revelry at the Indian Institute of Management Calcutta (IIMC). 
    
	After the Intaglio success, the Joka campus is now all set to host its annual cultural festival, Carpe Diem 2008 (being held in association with The Telegraph), from January 11 to 13.
    
	Among the participants are the IITs in Kharagpur and Guwahati, NIFT, Presidency College and St Xaviers College.
    
	The fest starts on Friday evening with Live Counterstrike, an inter-hostel competition.
    
	Razzmatazz, the fashion show, has been turned into an inter-college competition, said an organiser of Carpe Diem. Fashion enthusiasts from the participating institutes will walk the ramp for a prize money of Rs 50,000. Fashion designer Sabyasachi Mukherjee will judge the show.
    
	For theatre enthusiasts, a light-hearted adaptation of Chetan Bhagats Five Point Someone will be staged. Keeping pace with the time, IIMC is organising Apocalypse, a nightlong network gaming contest, with prizes worth Rs 1 lakh.
    
	In Armageddon, the rock contest, semi-pro bands from the state, Northeast, Delhi and Bangalore will vie for a pot of gold  a grand prize of Rs 80,000. A performance by Delhi-based rock band Prestorika will bring the fest to a close.
    
	Carpe Diem has been associated with the best and the biggest. This year, too, we will make sure the crowds and participants have an unforgettable experience, said Kanishk Khanna, a core member of Carpe Diem.
                                                                               
